\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 6. S. pseudocapsicum} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 184 (1753). Glabrous annual or perennial; stem 30-120 cm, erect, branched. Leaves 1·5-10 × 0·5-2 cm, oblong- to linear-lanceolate, acuminate, cuneate at base, entire to somewhat sinuate, alternate or in unequal pairs; petiole 0·2-2 cm. Cymes 1- to 3-flowered, solitary, extra-axillary to leaf-opposed, sessile. Calyx c. 5 mm, deeply incised; teeth linear-lanceolate. Corolla 10-15 mm in diameter, stellate, white. Anthers 3 mm, orange. Berry 10-15 mm in diameter, globose, red, shining, solitary.{\i  Widely cultivated for ornament and locally naturalized in S.W. Europe.} [Az Ga Lu.] ({\i E. South America.})
