\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 7. S. dulcamara} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 185 (1753) (incl. {\i S. littorale} Raab). Scrambling, glabrous to pubescent or densely villous-tomentose perennial, with simple hairs; stems 30-200 cm, woody below. Leaves (3-)5-9 × (1·5-)2·5-5(-9) cm, ovate, acute to acuminate, truncate, cordate or hastate at base, entire or with 1-4 lobes or small, stipitate pinnae at base; petiole up to 3 cm. Cymes usually with 10-25 or more flowers, lax, terminal, becoming lateral, several on extra-axillary peduncles usually much-branched 10-40 mm above base. Calyx c. 3 mm; teeth 0·5-1 mm, rounded. Corolla 10-15(-20) mm in diameter, stellate, dark purple (rarely white); lobes 7-10 mm, recurved, each with 2 greenish spots at base. Anthers 5-7 mm, pale yellow. Berry 10-15 × 7·5-10 mm, ovoid, red, shining. 2n = 24. {\i Damp woods, hedges, river-banks and sea-shores. Most of Europe except the extreme north.} All except Az Cr Fa Is Sb; only casual in Rs (N).
